<!DOCTYPE html>
<head>
<title>A learning experience</title>
<style>
.colourA {
    background-color: lightgreen;
    color:  black;
}
.colourB {
    background-color: lightyellow;
    color: black;
}
.colourC {
    background-color: lightgrey;
    color: black;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<h1>A learning experience</h1>
<h3>This learning experience is called 'A Button'</h3>
<p>Learn with me about buttons!</p>
<p>First, let's create a simple button:</p>
<button>Click me!</button>
<p>Did you know that you can disable a button?</p>
<button disabled>You can't click me!</button>
<p>What happens when we click a special button, like this one:</p>
<button onclick="alert('You clicked the special button!')">The special button</button>
<p>Did you know there are different types of buttons? Well here are some of the more popular button types:</p>
<button type="button">Just a regular button</button>
<button type="submit">A submit button</button>
<button type="reset">A reset button</button>
<p>Right now the submit and reset buttons are not doing anything. That is because the submit button sends the form data to a server and the reset button clears the form. Since we do not have a form here, they are not doing anything. But if we had a form, they would be very useful!</p>
<p>Lets create a form now!</p>
<form>
    <label for="name">Name:</label>
<input type="text" id="name" name="name"><br><br>

<button type="submit">Submit</button>
<button type="reset">Reset</button>
</form>
<p>Now try writing your name and then clicking the submit or reset button and see what happens!</p>
<p>If u submitted your name, we could use your name to personalize your experience on our website. For example, we could display a message like "Hello, [Your Name]!". Wait, we can do that right now! Just click the submit button and see what happens!</p>
<script>
    document.querySelector('form').addEventListener('submit', function(event) {
        event.preventDefault(); 
        const name = document.getElementById('name').value;
        alert('Hello, ' + name + '!');
    })
</script>
<button class="colourA colour-btn">A button with colour</button>
<button class="colourB colour-btn">A button with different colour</button>
<button class="colourC colour-btn">A button with another colour</button>

<script>
const colours = ['colourA', 'colourB', 'colourC'];
document.querySelectorAll('.colour-btn').forEach(button => {
    button.addEventListener('click', function() {
        const current = colours.find(c => this.classList.contains(c));
        const nextIndex = (colours.indexOf(current) + 1) % colours.length;
        this.classList.remove(current);
        this.classList.add(colours[nextIndex]);
    })
})
</script>

<button id="randomColour">A button with a random predefined colour</button>
<script>
 const coloursRandom = ['lightblue', 'lightpink'];
 const randomButton = document.getElementById('randomColour');
 function getRandomTime() {
    return Math.floor(Math.random() * 2000) + 1000;
 }
function changeColour() {
    const randomColour = coloursRandom[Math.floor(Math.random() * coloursRandom.length)];
    randomButton.style.backgroundColor = randomColour;
    setTimeout(changeColour, getRandomTime());
}
setTimeout(changeColour, getRandomTime());
</script>
<p>How about we combine both the random colour button and the colour changing button?</p>
<button id="combinedColour" class="colourA combinedBtn">This is a crazy combined button!</button>
<script>
    const combinedCol = ['colourA', 'colourB', 'colourC'];
document.querySelectorAll('.combinedBtn').forEach(button => {
    button.addEventListener('click', function() {
        const current = combinedCol.find(c => this.classList.contains(c));
        const nextIndex = (combinedCol.indexOf(current) + 1) % combinedCol.length;
        this.classList.remove(current);
        this.classList.add(combinedCol[nextIndex]);
        this.style.backgroundColor = '';
    });
});

const combinedColours = ['lightblue', 'lightpink'];
const combinedButton = document.getElementById('combinedColour');
function getRandomTimeC() {
    return Math.floor(Math.random() * 2000) + 1000;
}
function changeRandomColour() {
    const combinedRandomColour = combinedColours[Math.floor(Math.random() * combinedColours.length)];
    combinedButton.style.backgroundColor = combinedRandomColour;
    setTimeout(changeRandomColour, getRandomTimeC());
}
setTimeout(changeRandomColour, getRandomTimeC());
</script>
<p>How about we make a simple point system? Clicking a button will earn or deduct points.</p>
<p>Points: <span id="points">0</span></p>
<button id="earnPoint">Earn a point</button>
<button id="deductPoint">Deduct a point</button>
<script>
let points = 0;
document.getElementById('earnPoint').addEventListener('click', function() {
    points++;
    document.getElementById('points').textContent = points;
});
document.getElementById('deductPoint').addEventListener('click', function() {
    points--;
    document.getElementById('points').textContent = points;

});
</script>
<p>This is great and all, but what if we made it so that for button with a green colour we gain a point, but for red we deduct a point?</p>
<p>Points: <span id="testPoints">0</span></p>
<button id="pointBtn">Click me!</button>
<script>
let testPoints = 0;
const testColours = ['green', 'red'];
const testButton = document.getElementById('pointBtn');
function getRandomTestTime() {
    return Math.floor(Math.random() * 3000) + 2000;
}
function changeTestColour() {
    const randomTestColour = testColours[Math.floor(Math.random() * testColours.length)];
    testButton.style.backgroundColor = randomTestColour;
    setTimeout(function() {
        testButton.style.backgroundColor = '';
    }, getRandomTestTime() - 1500);
    setTimeout(changeTestColour, getRandomTestTime());
}

setTimeout(changeTestColour, getRandomTestTime());

document.querySelectorAll('#pointBtn').forEach(button => {
    button.addEventListener('click', function() {
        if (testButton.style.backgroundColor === 'green') {
            testPoints++;
            testButton.style.backgroundColor = '';
        } 
        else if (testButton.style.backgroundColor === 'red') {
            testPoints--;
            testButton.style.backgroundColor = '';
            if (testPoints < 0) {
                testPoints = 0;
            }
        }
        document.getElementById('testPoints').textContent = testPoints;
    });
});
</script>
<p>This simple game is a bit boring, so we could implement a high score system.</p>
<p>High Score: <span id="highScore">0</span></p>
<script>
 let highScore = localStorage.getItem('highScore') || 0;
 document.getElementById('highScore').textContent = highScore;
 document.querySelectorAll('#pointBtn').forEach(button => {
    button.addEventListener('click', function() {
        if (testPoints > highScore) {
            highScore = testPoints;
            localStorage.setItem('highScore', highScore);
            document.getElementById('highScore').textContent = highScore;
        }
    });
 });
</script>
<button id="resetBtn">Reset high score</button>
<script>
    document.getElementById('resetBtn').addEventListener('click', function() {
        highScore = 0;
        localStorage.setItem('highScore', highScore);
        document.getElementById('highScore').textContent = highScore;
    });
</script>
</body>
